</TD></TR></TABLE></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/urelkeb.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Relkeb</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Minstral of Mayhem</span><br>  Posts: 22<br> <font color=#333333>(5/2/02 3:41:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fthecrossroadstavern8833frm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=149.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: What is your religion in real life?</span><hr size=1> As far as Religion goes...<br>
<br>
I have a lot of respect for people who follow a Religion - and  I mean, actually live their life by what the Religion teaches - actually show some dedication to it by saying, &quot;no thanks, I can't do that because of what my Religion teaches.&quot;  I was raised in the Lutheran church, which is full of rituals, all of which I have no problem with except one.  <br>
<br>
To me, Religion is: Mankind ascribing earthly rituals, ceremonies, or practices to &quot;spiritual&quot; beliefs which are based on a standard - the Bible, the Koran, whatever.  No one believes (or should believe) in a Religion per se', but in the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> teachings</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of that Religion.  So to those of you who live life based on a particular Religion, my hat's off to you.<br>
<br>
I attend a Bible-believing Christian church that has done away with man-made rituals and just worships God and teaches from the Bible.  For me and my family, we'd rather worship the God of the Bible without being told when to stand up, when to sit down, when to say this, and when to say that.<br>
<br>
However, here's where I'm a bit confused.  People who say &quot;I believe what I choose to believe&quot; or &quot;I have my own belief system&quot; or similar statements.  My question to you is, what are you basing your beliefs on?  Doesn't there have to be something like a book or a person to base &quot;spiritual&quot; beliefs on?  Some kind of a standard?  <br>
<br>
The problem I see is that, without a standard, everything you do, say, or claim is pretty much situational.  I believe/say/act/do &quot;A&quot; in this given situation, but I do the oposite or something contradictory in situation &quot;B&quot; - much like politicians do.  Situational Ethics.  Situational Beliefs.  Situational Religion.  It's easy to do if you have no standard.<br>
<br>
Maybe I'm wrong, but I don't think people can just make something up and call it a belief system, or a Religion.  Because if you don't have a standard to at least measure yourself by, how can you possibly know if your own beliefs even have merrit - unless you've compaired them to some kind of Religion(s) that the world has to offer? <p><b><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=122926>Relkeb Ravenhawk<br>
Citizen of Surefall Glade</a>
